Betreff: Re: [tflearn/tflearn] data_utils.image_preloader does not work correctly under Windows 10 (#579)


It is working because the images are loaded on the fly (when they are needed), e.g. if you call X[1] it will load the image. That is why you dont see a ndarray of images after initiliazing the preloader but just a list of image paths.

This is really the expected behaviour, since you would use the image_preloader if you want to handle large datasets (hence you do not want to load them all at once at the beginning).

If you are interested in how this is implemented. You first have to look in data_utils.py at the base class Preloader<https://github.com/tflearn/tflearn/blob/3579931c121b228e00691f714b5ac0eb1b5e2c2e/tflearn/data_utils.py#L799-L813> and more specifically the function

 def __getitem__(self, id):

        if type(id) in [list, np.ndarray]:

            return [self.function(self.array[i]) for i in id]

        elif isinstance(id, slice):

            return [self.function(arr) for arr in self.array[id]]

        else:

return self.function(self.array[id])

This is where the [ ] operator is overloaded. Here you see that the function self.function(arr) is called. Now in implementation classes of the Preloader this function can be registered.
For example if you look at the class ImagePreloader<https://github.com/tflearn/tflearn/blob/3579931c121b228e00691f714b5ac0eb1b5e2c2e/tflearn/data_utils.py#L816>

class ImagePreloader(Preloader):

    def __init__(self, array, image_shape, normalize=True, grayscale=False):

        fn = lambda x: self.preload(x, image_shape, normalize, grayscale)

super(ImagePreloader, self).__init__(array, fn)

There the function 'self.preload' is registered. And finally you can look at this function to see what is actually happening when an item from an ImagePreloader is requested.

 def preload(self, path, image_shape, normalize=True, grayscale=False):

        img = load_image(path)

        width, height = img.size

        if width != image_shape[0] or height != image_shape[1]:

            img = resize_image(img, image_shape[0], image_shape[1])

        if grayscale:

            img = convert_color(img, 'L')

        img = pil_to_nparray(img)

        if normalize:

            img /= 255.

return img

