Re: implicit conversions, yea, I first thought about them too but didn't use them because there was validation of the tuple argument here (length check). I guess I forgot that the exceptions are consumed while the appropriate loader is being selected.

So this actually works as expected:

```cpp
// ...
        .def("__init__", [](Bar &self, py::tuple t) {
            if (py::len(t) != 2)
                throw std::runtime_error("oh no");
            new(&self) Bar(t[0].cast<int>(), t[1].cast<int>());
        })
// ...
    py::implicitly_convertible<py::tuple, Bar>();
```

allowing you to call `bar((10, 20))` from within Python and it works. It also doesn't accept tuples of wrong sizes.

